sec.p:
An important goal of our project is to move beyond general measures of positive and negative affect (H. J. Smith & Leach, 2004; Wheeler & Miyake, 1992) to the specific discrete emotions that are most likely to be associated with different comparison topics (R. H. Smith, 2000). Different emotions are associated with different action tendencies and antecedents (Frijda, Kuipers, & ter Schure, 1989
; 
Lazarus, 2001; Scherer, Schorr, & Johnstone, 2001; R. H. Smith, 2000). For example, anger, fear, and sadness all represent negative emotions, but anger is associated with active challenges toward particular targets, fear is associated with the desire to escape, and sadness is associated with withdrawal (Frijda et al., 1989; Scherer et al., 2001). In other words, different discrete emotions direct people’s attention and resources toward relevant goals and away from irrelevant goals (Hill, DelPriore, & Vaughan, 2011).
